                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "One cannot expect to \"reset\" the $_POST variable to null, an array, or any other value for that matter, without consequences when working with other code that depends on $_POST. In general, I think it cannot be best practices to empty the superglobals or to destroy the reference to the source data provided to a method. In any case, the component does not prevent another reference to the source data from existing:\n\n{code}\n$mypost = $_POST;\n$zfi = new Zend_Filter_Input($_POST);\n\/\/ $mypost is unaffected\n{code}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
